Introduction

In the world of conservation, engaging a broad range of stakeholders is often vital to the success of a project. Interactive online maps provide a powerful visualization tool for exploring relevant spatial products.

Goals:

  • Create your own interactive maps combining multiple layers and customizing symbology using the Leaflet library from R.

  • Create free public website using Github to house your interactive maps.

  • Create GeoJSON files using the rgdal package in R and see how Github automatically renders these with a Leaflet map.

1 Create Interactive Maps with Leaflet

You’ll create a series of maps to explore the different visualization options with the Leaflet library in R.

1.1 Create Rmarkdown document

Start by creating a lab folder. I use `H:/esm296-4f/lab5’.

Then create an Rmarkdown document in RStudio by going to the menu File, New File, R Markdown…

Save this document with the default text as map.Rmd in your lab folder. Click on “Knit HTML” in upper left of your text editing pane. In the rendered output you should see the text with formatting (eg bold, URL) and output from executing the chunks of R code, including the table of summary(cars) and figure from plot(cars). Note how these R chunks are surrounded by three backticks with {r} indicating that it is an R chunk to execute.

```{r}
summary(cars)
```

For more help with Rmarkdown, click on the “?”" in the upper right of the text editor pane to get links to the website “Using R Markdown” or the help “Markdown Quick Reference.” I also find the R Markdown cheat sheet to be useful.

You can now delete all the default text in this Rmarkdown document, except the header:

---
title: "maps"
author: "Ben Best"
date: "December 2, 2015"
output: html_document
---

## Create Map of Points

1.3 Create Map of Points

Start by creating a map of points that reads in the points from lab 3. You may have to change the path of your geodatabase which needs to contain the pts_tree feature class injected into the geodatabase at the end of lab 3.

suppressWarnings(suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(leaflet)
  library(rgdal)
}))

gdb = 'H:/esm296-4f/lab3/golf.gdb'
pts = readOGR(gdb, 'pts_tree', verbose=F)

# project points to geographic projection
pts_gcs = spTransform(pts, leaflet:::epsg4326)

# create map
leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(data = pts_gcs)

data=pts_gcs, popup=~sprintf(‘id: %d’, id))

# output to geojson writeOGR(sp, dsn=tmp, layer=‘dummy’, driver=‘GeoJSON’)

# move file file.rename(tmp, geo) } ```

leaflet:::epsg4326

GeoJSON

library(rgdal) # Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL) for R

gdb = 'H:/esm296-4f/lab3/golf.gdb'
dir = 'H:/esm296-4f/lab5_online/adv-gis/data'

# iterate through features in geodatabase
for (fc in ogrListLayers(gdb)){
  
  # print paths
  geo = sprintf('%s/%s.geojson', dir, fc)
  tmp = tempfile()
  cat(sprintf('gdb/fc: %s/%s\n  -> tmp: %s\n  -> geo: %s\n', gdb, fc, tmp, geo))
  
  # read in feature class
  sp = readOGR(gdb, fc)

  # output to geojson
  writeOGR(sp, dsn=tmp, layer='dummy', driver='GeoJSON')
  
  # move file
  file.rename(tmp, geo)
}

1.5 Get polygons of bristlecone pine distribution

Let’s continuing with our pet organism the bristlecone pine (Pinus longaeva). Download the species distribution shapefile from this website:

  • USGS GECSC: Tree Species Distribution Maps for North America

Unzip and create directories as needed so the shapefile and associated files live at this exact path:

H:\esm296-4f\lab5\raw\pinulong.shp

1.6 4. Generate points of bristlecone pine and create GeoJSON files

Let’s also get observation points of bristlecone pine to provide another type of vector data to display.

Copy the following scripts into RStudio and save to your lab5 homework location, ie H:\esm296-4f\github\lab5:

  • get_species.R pulls points from GBIF and outputs a shapefile

  • create_geojson.R converts shapefile of points and polygons into GeoJSON

Change the input variable USER to your Github username for the second script and run both in sequence so you should then have the following:

  • H:\esm296-4f\lab5\raw\
  • pinulong.shp - polygon shapefile
  • pts_pinulong.shp - point shapefile
  • H:\esm296-4f\bbest.github.io\map\
  • ply_pinulong.geojson - polygon GeoJSON file
  • pts_pinulong.geojson - points GeoJSON file

Push these scripts in H:\esm296-4f\github\lab5 to your Github site.

If the Git pane is not showing up in your “github” project, you will need to add the Git Bash path again: Tools > Global Options… Git/SVN > Git executable: Browse… and paste C:\Program Files (x86)\Git\bin\git.exe.

1.7 5. Open website files in RStudio and push GeoJSON files

Let’s use RStudio to push these created GeoJSON files and edit the HTML of the site. Go to File > New Project… > Existing Directory. Navigate to your H:296-4f.github.io folder. I recommend not opening this in a new window to reduce confusion.

You should see in your Git pane the “map” folder containing the GeoJSON files and other two files created by the new RStudio project listed as untracked status.

Check all of these to add, commit and push to your repository. Now visit your Github site https://github.com/USER/USER.github.io and navigate to the *.geojson files in your map directory.

You should see the points and polygons automatically rendered by Github in a little zoomable map with clickable popups showing the given feature’s attributes. Pretty cool!

1.8 6. Create Leaflet Mapper

But what about embedding these maps in your own website? And how about combining the points and polygons into a single map view?

To do this, we’ll use the same Javascript library as Github: Leaflet.js. Let’s put this in a simple URL on your website USER.github.io/map. By default web servers generally serve up an index.html for any given folder. So copy the index.html in the root of your site into a new map folder. To do this in RStudio’s Files pane, after creating New Folder map, tick index.html, More > Copy… map/index.html.

Now click on map/index.html > Open in Editor.

Let’s fix the link to the stylesheet which is now, relative to the map folder, one directory up. While we’re at it, let’s add the stylesheet and script needed for Leaflet.

Replace this line:

<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" media="screen" href="stylesheets/stylesheet.css">

with these:

<link rel="stylesheet" href="../stylesheets/stylesheet.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="../stylesheets/leaflet.awesome-markers.css">

<script>
  // create Leaflet map object and set view's center and zoom level
  var map = L.map('map').setView([38, -115], 7);

  // add background map layer
  var Esri_NatGeoWorldMap = L.tileLayer(
    'http://server.arcgisonline.com/ArcGIS/rest/services/NatGeo_World_Map/MapServer/tile/{z}/{y}/{x}');
  Esri_NatGeoWorldMap.addTo(map)
</script>

This should produce this interactive map:

Next, add the following lines of code between Esri_NatGeoWorldMap.addTo(map0) and </script> to map the points and polygons:

// add geojson of points
var pts = new L.GeoJSON.AJAX('./pts_pinulong.geojson');
pts.addTo(map)

// add GeoJSON of points
var ply = new L.GeoJSON.AJAX('./ply_pinulong.geojson');
ply.addTo(map)

This should produce the following interactive map after you commit and push:

Next, let’s customize the symbology so the points are green tree markers and polygons are orange.

We’re going to use the Leaflet.awesome-markers which enables you to use any of the nifty icons from Font-Awesome. To use this library we need to add some files zip prepped for you in this zip file you should download it to directly inside your H:\esm296-4f\USER.github.io folder:

Leaflet.awesome-markers_files.7z

Open it in 7-zip so you can see the files. Go ahead and right click on 7-zip > Extract Here to place the files in the necessary folders.

Replace the lines you last added above in map/index.html adding geojson points and polygons with these enanced versions:

// create tree marker
var treeMarker = L.AwesomeMarkers.icon({
  icon: 'tree',
  prefix: 'fa',
  markerColor: 'darkgreen',
  iconColor: 'white'});

// add geojson points with tree marker and popup
var pts = new L.GeoJSON.AJAX('./pts_pinulong.geojson', {
  pointToLayer: function (feature, latlng) {
    return L.marker(latlng, {icon: treeMarker});
  },
  onEachFeature: function (feature, layer) {
    layer.bindPopup(
      "Collected by: <strong>" + feature.properties.collctr + "</strong><br><br>" +
      "at: " + feature.properties.localty + "<br><br>" +
      "for: " + feature.properties.instttn, { maxWidth: 200 });
  }
});
pts.addTo(map)

// add geojson polygons with a style
var ply = new L.GeoJSON.AJAX('./ply_pinulong.geojson', {
  "color": "#ff7800",
  "weight": 5,
  "opacity": 0.65 });
ply.addTo(map)

This should produce the following interactive map after you commit and push:

2 Create Website to Host Map

2.1 Sign up for Github

Setup a free user account by visiting github.com.

Pick any untaken username (you can change your username later), use a *.edu email (for quicker approval later of educational discount) and set a password. Choose the free account.

2.2 Create Repository

Create a new repository called adv-gis at Github.com, presuming you are logged into the site. Yes, Initialize this repository with a README.

Now go to your repository Settings (upper right of navigation), and click on the Automatic page generator.

Clear the Body and enter the heading level 3 text ### Map like so:

Continue to layouts. Have fun choosing a layout aligned with your aesthetic sensibilities and Publish page.

This creates a new branch (ie an alternate set of files) called “gh-pages”. Let’s make this the default branch by going to Settings (upper right), Branches (left), and select “gh-pages” from the drop-down to switch it from “master”. Click Update. Accept the warning, and click “I understand, update the default branch.”

Now click on Code. You’ll notice some web files now in your repository: images, javascripts, stylesheets, and index.html. (The params.json is used internally for the automatic page generator.)

Now Edit your Description to add the URL https://USER.github.io/adv-gis (replacing USER with your Github username) to the Website entry at top next to Description and Save

Finally, check out your website! (Might take up to 10 minutes to appear)

2.3 Clone Repository Locally with RStudio

To copy the contents of the repository to your local machine is to “clone” it. Let’s use RStudio to do this. Open RStudio, navigate to menu Tools, and confirm RStudio knows to find the git executable at C:/Program Files/Git/bin/git.exe.

Navigate to menu File, New Project. Select Version Control, Git. Enter the URL of your repository and select an output location.

2.4 7. Add link from main site

To add a link from your root site USER.github.io, let’s add a link from the index.html there to map/index.html.

<h1>Welcome</h1>

Check out my <strong><a href='./map'>map of bristlecone pine</a></strong>.

Next Steps (optional)

The possibilities with Github are vast, but here at least are a few tips on next steps to get the most out of using Github.

2.5 Create your Personal Website

Create a new repository named username.github.io (where username is replaced with your Github username). Tick the box to Initialize this repository with a README. You can use the Automatic page generator (under Settings) like the lab to initialize web content which will be viewable at http://username.github.io. For more help, see pages.github.com.

2.6 Create your Organization Website

Create an organization such as for your PhD lab group or masters group project. Then you can add a new repository named organization.github.io (where organization is replaced with your Github organization name). You can use the Automatic page generator (under Settings) like the lab to initialize web content which will be viewable at http://username.github.io. For more help, see pages.github.com.

2.7 Get Free Private Repositories through Educational Discount

I recommend you also request the Github Educational Discount at education.github.com.

This signup will enable you to have free private repositories. Select Student, Individual account. You’ll need to provide some sort of image confirming your student status. I took a screen shot of an email verifying my enrollment. You shouldn’t see this note about a school-issued email address if you used your *.edu email. For “How do you plan to use Github”, something like: “I’ll be using a private repo to turn in assignments for a graduate level course on Advanced Topics in GIS (at the request of instructor @bbest). Hope to feel the stoke of playing with this trending tech!”

Usually only takes a couple days to grant you the Micro plan giving you 7 private repositories free of charge.
